leadership-approach|results_process_vision_people|application_1|1|Start with the outcome and owner|Start by naming the outcome, the decision needed, and who owns the next step. Put this into one clear sentence before the meeting or task moves on, then state what visible progress should exist by the end of the day.|results|active|leadership-approach::results_process_vision_people::application_1
leadership-approach|results_process_vision_people|application_2|2|Stabilise with Process, then add Vision|Before you move on, use Process to turn intent into steps, responsibilities, and a cleaner handover. Then bring in Vision to connect the immediate task to the reason, consequence, or better option. This gives the work a stronger middle step before you rely on the full pattern.|process|active|leadership-approach::results_process_vision_people::application_2
leadership-approach|results_process_vision_people|application_3|3|Bring in People when the work tightens|When the work starts to narrow, bring in People deliberately. In practice, speak with the people most affected and clarify what they need to know, trust, or contribute. Do this before the first two signals have answered the problem so completely that the wider need is harder to see.|people|active|leadership-approach::results_process_vision_people::application_3
